<h2>Origins & History</h2>

<p>Prosecco's story begins in the rolling hills of northeastern Italy, where the <strong>Glera grape</strong> (formerly known as Prosecco) has thrived for over a millennium. Historical records trace this indigenous variety back to Roman times in the village of Prosecco, near Trieste, where it earned its original name. The grape found its true calling in the Veneto region, particularly in the steep, mineral-rich soils of Valdobbiadene and Conegliano.</p>

<p>DNA analysis has revealed Glera's fascinating parentage: it's a natural cross between <strong>Glera Lunga and Malvasia Bianca Lunga</strong>, explaining its distinctive aromatic profile and natural acidity. This genetic heritage contributes to Prosecco's characteristic white flower aromatics and crisp, refreshing character that has captivated wine lovers worldwide.</p>

<p>The transformation from local curiosity to global phenomenon occurred gradually. The <strong>Charmat method</strong>, developed by Eugène Charmat in 1907, revolutionized Prosecco production by enabling tank fermentation that preserved the grape's delicate fruit flavors. This technique, adopted by forward-thinking producers like Carpené Malvolti in 1868, allowed Prosecco to maintain its fresh, approachable character while achieving consistent quality.</p>

<h3>Modern Recognition and Global Expansion</h3>

<p>Prosecco's reputation soared internationally following World War II, with exports beginning in earnest during the 1960s. The creation of <strong>DOCG status for Conegliano Valdobbiadene</strong> in 2009 elevated the finest expressions to Italy's highest quality tier, while the broader Prosecco DOC encompasses production across nine provinces.</p>

<p>Today, Prosecco represents one of wine's greatest success stories. Global plantings have expanded to over <strong>24,000 hectares</strong>, with production reaching 600 million bottles annually. While Italy remains the undisputed leader, countries including Australia, Argentina, and Brazil now cultivate Glera, though none can replicate the unique terroir of the Veneto's chalky soils and cool Alpine breezes that give authentic Prosecco its distinctive mineral backbone and elegant effervescence.</p>

<h2>Grape Characteristics & Winemaking</h2>

<p>Prosecco's foundation lies in the <strong>Glera grape</strong> (formerly known as Prosecco), a variety that thrives in the specific climatic conditions of northeastern Italy. Understanding how this grape behaves from vineyard to bottle reveals why quality varies so dramatically across different Prosecco options.</p>

<h3>Viticulture and Growing Requirements</h3>

<p>Glera is a naturally vigorous variety that requires careful canopy management to prevent overcropping. The grape performs best in well-draining soils with good sun exposure, particularly on the steep hillsides of Valdobbiadene and Conegliano where DOCG Proseccos are produced. <strong>Harvest timing is crucial</strong>—picked too early and the wines lack body; too late and they lose the bright acidity essential for quality sparkling wine. Premium producers typically harvest in late September to early October, when Glera reaches 10.5-11.5% potential alcohol with refreshing acidity levels around 7-8 g/L.</p>

<p>The best sites limit yields to 13-15 tons per hectare, though DOC regulations permit up to 18 tons. This yield difference significantly impacts concentration and ultimately, wine quality.</p>

<h3>Winemaking Techniques</h3>

<p>The <strong>Charmat method</strong> (tank fermentation) is Prosecco's defining production technique, designed to preserve Glera's delicate floral and fruit characteristics. Primary fermentation occurs in stainless steel tanks at controlled temperatures (16-18°C) to maintain freshness. Most producers avoid malolactic fermentation to preserve crisp acidity, though some premium examples undergo partial MLF for added complexity.</p>

<p>Secondary fermentation takes place in pressurized tanks with selected yeasts over 30-40 days. The wine remains on its lees during this period, contributing to texture and subtle yeasty notes. <strong>Oak is rarely used</strong>, as it would mask Glera's inherent character of white flowers, green apple, and citrus.</p>

<h3>Regional Expression</h3>

<p>Prosecco di Valdobbiadene DOCG showcases mineral-driven precision thanks to its steep, south-facing slopes and calcareous soils. Wines from Cartizze, the region's grand cru, display exceptional elegance and honeyed complexity. Prosecco di Conegliano DOCG tends toward more fruit-forward expressions, while broader DOC wines from the plains offer simpler, more commercial styles.</p>

<h3>Quality Indicators</h3>

<p>Premium Proseccos display <strong>persistent, fine bubbles</strong>, bright acidity (6-7 g/L), and complex aromatics beyond simple fruit. Look for wines showing mineral undertones, balanced residual sugar (typically 12-17 g/L for Brut), and clean, lengthy finishes. Superior examples often feature hand-harvested fruit and extended lees contact.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential</h3>

<p>Unlike Champagne, Prosecco is designed for immediate consumption. Most examples peak within 18-24 months of production, though exceptional DOCG bottlings can develop honeyed complexity over 3-4 years. The wine's fresh, primary fruit character gradually gives way to more mature notes, but extended aging typically diminishes rather than enhances quality.</p>

