<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike many still wines, <strong>prosecco's charm lies in its youthful exuberance</strong>, though different quality tiers offer varying cellaring potential that reflects their production methods and terroir expression.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> reaches peak quality within 18-24 months of disgorgement, with tank-method production preserving primary fruit aromatics that begin diminishing after two years. <strong>Prosecco DOCG Conegliano Valdobbiadene</strong> demonstrates superior longevity—3-5 years for most bottlings—thanks to superior vineyard sites and longer lees contact. Premium <strong>Cartizze</strong> and <strong>Rive</strong> designations can evolve beautifully for 5-8 years, developing honeyed complexity while maintaining their characteristic minerality.</p>

<h3>Evolution Characteristics</h3>

<p>Young prosecco displays vibrant green apple, pear, and citrus notes with pronounced effervescence. With proper aging, these primary fruits evolve into more complex <strong>orchard fruit and stone fruit flavors</strong>, while the mousse becomes creamier and more integrated. Prosecco DOCG develops subtle <strong>almond and brioche notes</strong> from extended lees contact, though it never reaches the oxidative complexity of traditional method sparkling wines.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store prosecco at <strong>50-55°F (10-13°C)</strong> with 70% humidity in a dark environment. Unlike still wines, keep bottles <strong>upright for short-term storage</strong> (under one year) to minimize wine-cork contact, or on their side for longer aging to keep corks moist.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>

<p>Open <strong>Prosecco DOC within 2 years</strong> for optimal freshness. <strong>DOCG bottlings shine between years 2-4</strong>, when fruit intensity balances with emerging complexity. <strong>Cartizze reaches peak elegance at 3-5 years</strong>, displaying its signature floral refinement.</p>

<p>Signs of proper aging include <strong>deeper golden color and integrated bubbles</strong>. Avoid bottles showing browning, flat aromatics, or excessive sediment—indicators of oxidation or heat damage.</p>

