    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when selecting Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all Prosecco tastes the same—quality varies dramatically between mass-market brands and estate producers like Nino Franco or Bisol. Many people also overlook the sweetness level, choosing "Dry" when they want crisp wine, or serve Prosecco too warm, which masks its delicate aromatics. Always check the DOCG/DOC designation and serve at 40-45°F for optimal expression.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long does Prosecco stay fresh after opening compared to other sparkling wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco typically maintains its best quality for 1-3 days after opening when properly sealed and refrigerated, shorter than traditional method sparkling wines due to larger, less persistent bubbles. Use a proper sparkling wine stopper rather than a regular cork, and consume tank method Prosecco sooner than bottle-fermented wines. The fresh fruit character that makes Prosecco appealing also makes it more susceptible to oxidation than aged sparkling wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What alternatives should I consider if I enjoy Prosecco's style?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Try Cava from Spain for similar fresh fruit character at lower prices, or explore other Italian sparkling wines like Franciacorta for more complexity, or Lambrusco for food-friendly versatility. Austrian Grüner Veltliner Sekt offers comparable minerality and freshness, while Loire Valley Crémant provides elegant alternatives with different grape varieties. These options expand your sparkling wine repertoire while maintaining the approachable, food-friendly style that makes Prosecco popular.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Prosecco producers offer the best value in different price ranges?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">In the $10-15 range, La Marca and Mionetto offer consistent quality, while $15-25 brings excellent options like Nino Franco Rustico and Villa Sandi. For premium experiences ($25-40), seek out Bisol, Adami, or Case Bianche from top DOCG zones. These producers maintain quality across vintages and offer authentic expressions of their respective terroirs, providing better value than mass-market brands at similar price points.</p>
